\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "2 GPGIs"

\end_inset

Global Public Good Institutions (GPGIs): 4 examples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(vague) We shall mean by a 'Global Public Good Institution' (GPGI) any instituti
on that uses money to cause increases in the provision of a particular global
 public good that it is dedicated to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A donor-independent GPGI is a GPGI whose actions only depend on its aggregate
 budget but not on the vector of donor contributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
CEPI (The Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovation) (existing since
 2017)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "CEPI"
target "http://www.cepi.org/"

\end_inset

 has so far mostly been focussing on advancing vaccines against known threats.
 Recently, it has started to also fund new platform technologies with the
 potential to accelerate the development and manufacture of vaccines against
 previously unknown pathogens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB and Malaria (existing since 2002)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This GPGI allocates funding for programs against AIDS, TB and Malaria.
 Allocations made to countries are 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "proportional"
target "https://www.theglobalfund.org/media/5642/fundingmodel_allocations2017-2019detailedexplanation_report_en.pdf?u=636898879780000000"

\end_inset

 to the disease burden for each of the three diseases and to an index of
 economic capacity calculated based on per capita GDP.
 The Global Fund works closely together with another GPGI, called UNITAID,
 which has been financed through 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "ticket taxes"
target "http://www.leadinggroup.org/rubrique177.html"

\end_inset

 on international flights since 2006.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "FCCP: The-Forest-Carbon"

\end_inset

 (existing since 2011)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
This 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Fund"
target "https://www.forestcarbonpartnership.org/carbon-fund-0"

\end_inset

 rewards countries with tropical forest as a function of the policies they
 pursue to conserve their tropical forests.
 In the future this institution will also condition its payments on results
 (amount of tropical forests conserved), as Norway already does in bilateral
 contracts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
ITER (The International Thermonuclear Reactor) (existing since 2007)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "ITER"
target "https://www.iter.org/"

\end_inset

is an international nuclear fusion research and engineering megaproject.
 Its stated goal is to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demonstrate the scientific and technological feasibility of fusion energy
 for peaceful use
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Global Public Good Institutions 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "4 sec:Global-Public-Good"

\end_inset

financed via voluntary contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have been implicitly assuming that the voluntary contributions
 that countries make to the GPGIs are unaffected by the contributions made
 via the MCT mechanism.
 We will later try to better understand how these voluntary contributions
 might change endogenously in response to changes in financing from other
 sources such as the MCT mechanism.
 In preparation for that task we will study the question of how voluntary
 contributions to a given GPGI will endogenously change in response to a
 change in an exogenous additional funding for that GPGI.
 This question is also relevant in its own right, for example for assessing
 existing proposals to use global resources to finance particular GPGIs,
 as we will discuss later 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Examples-of-proposals for capturing global resources"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A model of for the voluntary contributions to Donor Independent GPGIs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all countries is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 There is a private good and a set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of donor independent GPGIs.
 Each country 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 chooses its consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the private good and its vector 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 of voluntary (monetary) contributions to the GPGIs (where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{ik}\geq0$
\end_inset

 denotes country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's contribution to GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

).
 Country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's utility is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(c_{i},Q)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 denotes the vector of aggregate (monetary) contributions.
 Here the aggregate contribution to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in K$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}=\sum_{i\in I}q_{ik}$
\end_inset

.
 Country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's budget constraint is that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}+\sum_{k\in K}q_{ik}\leq y_{i}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is exogenous.
 Each country takes the other countries' choices as given and chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $(c_{i},\{q_{ik},k\in K\})$
\end_inset

 so as to maximise 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(c_{i},Q)$
\end_inset

 under the budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}+\sum_{k\in K}q_{ik}\leq y_{i}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:(restatement-of-the"

\end_inset

(restatement of the neutrality theorem from Sandler and Posnett (1991) 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/109114219101900102"

\end_inset

 in our terminology) Suppose that at the status quo the GPGIs are entirely
 financed through voluntary contributions.
 Suppose that each country's payoff from a GPGI is a concave function of
 the money available for that GPGI.
 Consider a reform consisting of imposing lump sum taxes on a set of countries
 each of which voluntarily contributes some money to some GPGI, such that
 no country is taxed more than its status quo aggregate contribution to
 GPGIs.
 Suppose all the money raised through these lump sum taxes is allocated
 to the GPGIs, with none of the transfers exceeding the total funding at
 the status quo for any GPGI.
 Then the reform has no effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 faces the problem to maximise 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(c_{i},Q)$
\end_inset

 subject to the constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}+\sum_{k\in K}(Q_{k}-(\sum_{j\neq i}q_{jk}+G_{k}))\leq y_{i}-L_{i}$
\end_inset

with the further constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}\geq G_{k}+\sum_{j\neq i}q_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can rewrite this problem by eliminating 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
maximise 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(y_{i}-L_{i}-\sum_{k\in K}(Q_{k}-(\sum_{j\neq i}q_{jk}+G_{k})),Q)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}\geq G_{k}+\sum_{j\neq i}q_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the situation without the transfers, i.e.
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}=0\forall i$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tilde{q_{ik}})_{i\in I,k\in K}$
\end_inset

 is a Nash equilibrium.
 Now consider a global mechanism that consists of contributing 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{k}$
\end_inset

 to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, financed by the lump sum taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}\leq y_{i}-\tilde{c_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{k}\leq\sum_{i}\tilde{q_{ik}}$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider any 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{q_{ik}})_{i\in I,k\in K}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q_{ik}}\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q_{ik}}>0\,iff\,\tilde{q_{ik}}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\hat{q_{ik}}+G_{k}=\sum_{i}\tilde{q_{ik}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\hat{q_{ik}}+L_{i}=\sum_{k}\tilde{q_{ik}}\forall k\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose there is a profitable deviation for player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q_{ik}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{ik}^{*}$
\end_inset

 .
 Then by the asssumed convexity of the payoff from 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, there would also be a profitable deviation for player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{q_{ik}}$
\end_inset

 consisting of decreasing it marginally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
(Almost a neutrality theorem)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "(Almost-a-neutrality"

\end_inset

 Suppose that at the status quo the GPGIs are entirely financed through
 voluntary contributions.
 Consider a reform that raises an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{F\leq\sum_{i\in I,k\in K}\tilde{q_{ik}}}}$
\end_inset

 of money from non-contributors (i.e.
 from countrie that do not contribute to any of the GPGIs) and and allocates
 this money to the GPGIs in such a way that for each of the GPGI the transfer
 does not exceed the funding available at the status quo.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 denote the resulting allocation and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 denote the set of contributors to global public goods at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a set of lump sum transfers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{j}\geq0,j\in J\}$
\end_inset

 distributing the money 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to the contributors, i.e.
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j\in J}t_{j}=F$
\end_inset

 such that the resulting allocation is 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
proof
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The intervention 'raising money for the GPGIs from non-contributors in a
 lump sum way' can be written as a sum of 'raising money for the GPGIs from
 contributors in a lump sum way' + 'redistributing money from the non-contributo
rs to the contributors'.
 By proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:(restatement-of-the"

\end_inset

 the first of these interventions satisfies neutrality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us analyse the MCT mechanism at taxation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{x^{\#}}}$
\end_inset

.
 To do that, consider starting at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and increasing the rate to 
\begin_inset Formula $dx>0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be the proportion of money raised from countries that do not contribute
 to any GPGIs.
 Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(Almost-a-neutrality"

\end_inset

 predicts that this is equivalent to some lump sum transfer from the countries
 that at the status quo do not make any voluntary contributions to GPGIs
 to countries that at the status quo do make voluntary contributions to
 some GPGIs.
 Also, it predicts that it does not matter to which contributor the money
 is given.
 Supposing that this transfer does not change the proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 of money that the contributors give to GPGIs, this would mean a dollar
 raised via the MCT for GPGIs would only result in 
\begin_inset Formula $pz$
\end_inset

 dollars of actual increase in funding for GPGIs.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is smaller than 1% for all countries, this shows that the conclusion is
 almost as pessimistic as in a situation in which the neutrality theorem
 applies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:A-model-for voluntary"

\end_inset

A model for the game of voluntary contributions to a Global Public Good
 Institution (GPGI)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A model for the case of Direct Procurement GPGIs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 denotes the set of all countries.
 Each country 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 chooses the voluntary contribution 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 to the GPGI in question.
 The GPGI then takes an action 
\begin_inset Formula $z(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are using that by the definition of Direct Procurement GPGIs, the
 action 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 of the GPGI depends only on the total money 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at its disposal.
 Country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's payoff is: 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(z(Q))-h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Microfoundations for the payoff function 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(x_{i}(Q),x_{-i}(Q))-h_{i}(q_{i})+g_{i}(R_{i})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benefit 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(x_{i},x_{-i})$
\end_inset

 that the player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 internalises can incorporate pure altruism.
 In fact, this seems necessary to explain Norway's and Sweden's high contributio
ns to global public goods.
 Given that these countries only have populations of 5 million and 10 million,
 respectively, the partial internalisation of the benefits of global public
 goods can hardly account for these countries' contributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 might write as: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})=c_{i}(q_{i})-s_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 could represent the net expected political cost.
 This could on the one hand include both the opportunity cost of public
 funds and the risk that domestic political forces will discredit the government
 for some constituencies that would accuse it to not act in the national
 interest.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 could include the benefit of earning the support of citizens in favor of
 altruistic action as well as the diplomatic recognition and reputation
 internationally.
 It is then plausible that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}'>0,c_{i}''>0,s_{i}'>0,s_{i}''<0$
\end_inset

, which would imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}''(q_{i})>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the litterature modelling the voluntary contributions of states (ref)
 it is assumed that in their decision how much to voluntarily contribute
 to GPGIs countries only consider the benefit of marginal funding to the
 GPGI and the opportunity costs of funds.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Implications-for-the opportunity costs"

\end_inset

 we will see that this would imply that the 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 is almost perfectly flat on the relevant range.
 This is why the following proposition will be of interest:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "flat costs"

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})=q_{i}\forall i$
\end_inset

.
 Then almost surely only one player contributes money to the GPGI in the
 first stage of the game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Consider the marginal benefits 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q}$
\end_inset

 of additional money provided the GPGI in question.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}(i)$
\end_inset

 be the set of funding levels at which country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is indifferent between contributing a bit more or a bit less.
 Almost surely, each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}(i)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Hence for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 almost surely 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}(i)\cap S^{*}(j)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are to both contribute at the Nash equilibrium, this can only happen at
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\in S^{*}(i)\cap S^{*}(j)$
\end_inset

, a set that is empty with probability 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will in the next subsection see examples of GPGIs for which several countries
 make voluntary contributions.
 Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "flat costs"

\end_inset

 suggests that 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 must have significant convexity in order for the model to be able to reproduce
 the observed pattern of voluntary contributions, in which for each GPGI
 typically a substantial number of countries contributes.
\end_layout

