</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that for all countries and all global institutions for which we have
 given the data here, the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{q_{i}}{GDP_{i}-q_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is very close to 0.
 This will still be true for all the other global institutions and for other
 specifications of how a government's payoff depends on its available money.
 In other words: If we assume that countries' costs of contributions is
 determined by their opportunity costs of the money, then we obtain that
 a constant marginal cost function would be an extremely good approximation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "flat costs"

\end_inset

 that this would imply that we should expect there to be only one contributing
 country for each GPGI.
 However, for the examples we have seen (CEPI, GAVI, Global Fund for AIDS,
 TB and Malaria, Forest Carbon Partnership) there are always several contributin
g countries.
 Thus we can conclude that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 must contain more components than just the opportunity costs of funds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Crowding-out-of voluntary contributions"

\end_inset

Crowding out of voluntary contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall analyse a donor-indpendent GPGI.
 We shall use the utility specification 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(M)-h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the total amount of money at the disposal of the GPGI.
 We will consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the sum of an external amount 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and the aggregate voluntary contributions 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 This specification contains as a special case the model for the Direct
 Procurement GPGIs that we defined above, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(z)-h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, since the action 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that the GPGI will take will be determined by its available money, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 It also contains as a special case the specification that we used above
 for analyzing Reward Payment based GPGIs, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(x_{i}(M),x_{-i}(M))-h_{i}(q_{i})+g_{i}(R_{i})$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, at least if we assume that there is a unique subgame perfect Nash equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Crowding-out for exogenous donation to a given GPGI"

\end_inset

 Consider a GPGI that is financed by an exogenous donation of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and by voluntary contributions by governments that are determined as a
 Nash equilibrium given 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Denoting the elasticities of marginal benefits and marginal costs by 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{h_{i}'}$
\end_inset

, respectively, and supposing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}\leq1$
\end_inset

, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}=\frac{\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}{1-\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The government of country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 has payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(Q+F)-h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in Contributors$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is determined by the FOC, which is: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dU_{i}}{dq_{i}}=u_{i}'(Q+F)-h_{i}'(q_{i})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiating this FOC with respect to F yields:
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{dQ}{dF}+1)u_{i}''(Q+F)-\frac{dq_{i}}{dF}h_{i}''(q_{i})=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Now using again the FOC we can rewrite this as: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dq_{i}}{dF}=(\frac{dQ}{dF}+1)\frac{u_{i}''(Q+F)}{u_{i}'(Q+F)}\frac{h_{i}'(q_{i})}{h_{i}''(q_{i})}=(\frac{dQ}{dF}+1)\frac{u_{i}''(Q+F)(Q+F)}{u_{i}'(Q+F)}\frac{h_{i}'(q_{i})}{h_{i}''(q_{i})q_{i}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}=(\frac{dQ}{dF}+1)\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Summing over all contributors yields: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}=(\frac{dQ}{dF}+1)\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}$
\end_inset

.
 From this we deduce: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}=\frac{\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}{1-\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}=\frac{\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}{1-\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}$
\end_inset

.
 First consider the case where all the marginal benefits are concave, i.e.
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}\leq0\forall i\in Contributors$
\end_inset

 and where all the marginal cost curves are convex, i.e.
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{h_{i}'}\geq\text{0}\forall i\in Contributors$
\end_inset

.
 In this case the smaller the elasticities of the marginal costs are, the
 more crowding out there is.
 Moreover if all the elasticities of the marginal costs are very close to
 0 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}$
\end_inset

 is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, meaning that there is close to full crowding out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}=0\forall i\in Contributors$
\end_inset

.
 then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In other words: If the curves for the marginal benefit as a function of
 the available money to the global institution are flat, then the 'naive
 view' that evaluates the impact of additional funding contributed by a
 philantropist or raised through international taxes without taking into
 account the endogenous change in voluntary constributions is correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 (This can happen if some of the contributors' marginal benefit curves are
 locally convex around the equilibrium.) In this case we see that there is
 actually 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crowding in
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}>0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}>1$
\end_inset

 there will even be a discontinuous jump in the equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see why this happens, we note that from the second order conditions we
 can only establish: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}''(Q+F)\leq h_{i}''(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, which using the FOC can be rewritten as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{u_{i}''(Q+F)}{u_{i}'(Q+F)}\leq\frac{h_{i}''(q_{i})}{h_{i}'(q_{i})}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\frac{u_{i}''(Q+F)}{u_{i}'(Q+F)}}{\frac{h_{i}''(q_{i})}{h_{i}'(q_{i})}}\leq1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}\leq1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is not sufficient to ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}\leq1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "5 sec:Multiple-Cause-Treaties"

\end_inset

Mechanisms for harnessing global revenues for multiple GPGIs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Examples-of-proposals for capturing global resources"

\end_inset


\size normal
Examples
\size default
 of proposals for capturing global resources
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Special Drawing Rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/policy/wess/wess_current/2012wess_overview_en.pdf"

\end_inset

 it is suggested that: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new international [could be created] through the issuance of special drawing
 rights (SDRs) by the International Monetary Fund, to be allocated with
 a bias favoring developing countries or leveraged as development financing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Revenues-seabed"

\end_inset

Revenues from the ownership of global resources: “royalties” obtained from
 natural resource extraction beyond territorial limits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/policy/wess/wess_current/2012wess_overview_en.pdf"

\end_inset

 it is suggested that: “royalties” obtained from natural resource extraction
 beyond territorial limits, such as from the oceans beyond territorial limits,
 Antarctica or outer space, could be tapped for international development
 cooperation.
 As global resources lie outside national jurisdictions, any licensing and
 payment of royalties would have to involve an international authority that
 was recognized as the responsible agent for managing the specific commons.
 While fishing in international waters and other activities in the “commons”
 might be licensed in this way, only revenues from mining the seabed has
 thus far been seen as a source of international public revenue.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How to use the revenue from global resources?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/policy/wess/wess_current/2012wess_overview_en.pdf"

\end_inset

 the authors propose to use the money captured from global resources be
 used for ODA.
 We will now define and explore an alternative proposal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An example of a mechanism leveraging voluntary contributions: The Proportional
 Matching Fund mechanism (PMF)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: PMF"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The Proportional Matching Fund (PMF) would be a newly created global institution
 that would have a set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 of 'eligible Global Public Good Institutions'.
 (For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 could be 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
{CEPI,GlobalFund,The Forest Carbon Partnership's Carbon Fund, the proposed
 RES-Fund under the auspices of the International Renewable Energy Agency}
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
or 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 could encompass all GPGIs.) The PMF would pay out its available money 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to the GPGIs in 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 in proportion to the voluntary contributions made to the various institutions
 .
 In other words, the PMF would each year look at the budget 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{j}$
\end_inset

 of each GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in J$
\end_inset

 and pay to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 the amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{Q_{j}}{\sum_{k\in J}Q_{k}}F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "PMF crowding in and out"

\end_inset

We consider the marginal effect of the first dollar of a newly introduced
 Proportional Matching Fund with an associated set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 of eligible GPGIs.
 Let us assume that at the status quo each GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in J$
\end_inset

 is financed entirely by the voluntary contributions by governments.
 Moreover, suppose that the profile of contributions is always a Nash equilibriu
m in the game.
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $Contributors_{a}(F)$
\end_inset

 the set of countries making strictly positive voluntary contributions to
 the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i,a}(F)$
\end_inset

 the voluntary contribution of country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in J$
\end_inset

, by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{a}(F):=\sum_{i\in I}q_{i,a}(F)=\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(F)}q_{i,a}(F)$
\end_inset

 the aggregate amount of contributions made to GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(F):=\sum_{j\in J}Q_{j}(F)$
\end_inset

 the aggregate amount of contributions made to all GPGIs in total.
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}:=\frac{Q_{a}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}}\frac{\partial^{2}u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 the elasticity at 
\begin_inset Formula $F=0$
\end_inset

 of the marginal benefit of additional funding for the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 accruing to country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and by 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}:=\frac{q_{i,a}}{\frac{\partial h_{i,a}}{\partial q_{i,a}}}\frac{\partial^{2}h_{i,a}}{\partial q_{i,a}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
the elasticiy at 
\begin_inset Formula $F=0$
\end_inset

 of the subjective marginal cost for the government of country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of making voluntary contributions to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}>0$
\end_inset

 Then if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{1}\text{+\text{\ensuremath{\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(0)}\frac{q_{i,a}}{Q_{a}}\frac{-\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}}}}>0$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}|_{F=0}=\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(0)}\frac{q_{i,a}}{Q}\left(\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}+\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}(\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}})\right)\frac{1}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}}}}{\text{1}\text{+\text{\ensuremath{\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(0)}\frac{q_{i,a}}{Q_{a}}\frac{-\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}}}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}|_{F=0}$
\end_inset

 was obtained through long computations using Mathematica.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}}\frac{q_{ai}}{Q_{a}}=1$
\end_inset

 , we can deduce from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{-\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}\geq-1\forall i\in Contributors_{a}$
\end_inset

 that the denominator, 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{1}\text{+\text{\ensuremath{\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(0)}\frac{q_{i,a}}{Q_{a}}\frac{-\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}}}}$
\end_inset

, is positive.
 Let us from now on focus on the generic case in which this is strictly
 positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in Contributor_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}=1,$
\end_inset

 the numerator, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}$
\end_inset

, is a weighted average of the marginal utility that country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 gets from additional financing for the other GPGIs (i.e.
 excluding 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

), weighted in proportion to the financing that these receive.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in Contributor_{a}$
\end_inset

, it is plausible that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}}\leq1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we see that the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}|_{F=0}$
\end_inset

 is determined by two forces.
 Firstly, there is the positive term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}(\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}})$
\end_inset

, which arises from the fact that the marginal increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 increases country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's incentive to voluntarily contribute, since by doing so it can move money
 to its preferred GPGI, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, shifting it away from the other GPGIs.
 The size of this effect is proportional to the proportion of money going
 to the other GPGIs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Secondly, there is the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}>0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 if there are increasing marginal benefits accruing to country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 from money going to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, then we obtain the conclusion that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}+\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}(\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}})>0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus in this case there is always 'crowding in' of voluntary contributions
 to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 from country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We also see that the size of this effect increases in 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, there is no theoretical bound on how strong the crowding-in can
 be, as we will prove in corollary below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}<0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 when there are decreasing marginal benefits accruing to country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 from money going to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently negative then there will be crowding out of contributions
 from country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 for the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically the condition for there to be crowding out is 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\frac{-\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}}{\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}}>1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\forall i\in Contributors_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 For the limit we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\epsilon_{u_{ai}}^{a}\rightarrow-\infty}\text{\text{\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}}}=-1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This makes sense: If for some country the marginal benefit drops off all
 of a sudden exactly at the current level of financing for the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, then the aggregate contribution to the GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 cannot increase until country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's contribution has been fully crowded out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{set\,of\,all\,models}min\{\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}|_{F=0}:a\in J\}=\infty$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
proof: Suppose we have any model with corresponding Nash equilibrium such
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}+\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}(\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}})>0\forall a\in J\forall i\in Contributor_{a}$
\end_inset

 at this Nash equilibrium.
 Let us keep the model to first order unchanged around the Nash equilibrium
 but multiply all the elasticities by the same factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<1$
\end_inset

.
 Then the second order conditions for the best responses are still satisfied.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}|_{F=0}$
\end_inset

 increases, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}(\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}})>0$
\end_inset

 and we can make this increase arbitrarily large if we choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 sufficiently close to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Which GPGIs should be included in the MCT and the PMF, respectively?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-GPGI-selection PMF"

\end_inset

The GPGI selection problem for the PMF mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is a set of governments who are considering setting up a PMF.
 Specifically, suppose that they are ready to voluntarily contribute money
 to this PMF and that there is a chance that by doing so they could acquire
 recognition for moral leadership that would allow them to get all countries
 to consider the proposal of allocating the revenues generated from the
 deep sea resources to the PMF instead of paying them out to countries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the decision problem of the set of people who have the opportunity
 to give advice to these governments that are considering setting up a PMF.
 Which set of GPGIs should the advisors recommend to be included in the
 PMF? There are least three important considerations to be taken into account:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) The global benefit, evaluated from an impartial perspective, that is
 generated per additional dollar available for the GPGI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) The crowding out/ crowding in of voluntary contributions to the GPGIs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) The distribution of payoffs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider first the global benefit, evaluated from an impartial perspective.
 There are strong reasons to think that reducing existential risks could
 be of enourmous value in expectation (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "www.existential-risk.org/concept.pdf"

\end_inset

).
 Global pandemics might be one of the largest existential risks.
 Advancing research aimed at improving the capacity for the world to quickly
 develop vaccines when faced with new pathogens could be an effective way
 to reduce this risk.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28806130"

\end_inset

 This would imply that CEPI might be one of the most valuable GPGIs.
 This consideration would weigh strongly in favor of including CEPI in the
 PMF mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to estimate the global benefit that the PMF generates, it is potentiall
y important to take into account the amount of crowding out/crowding in
 that takes place.
 Switching from a regime (that currently appears to be envisaged) where
 the revenue from the seabed resources from the high sea are paid out to
 countries to a regime where this money is instead paid out to some GPGI
 is equivalent to implementing lump sum taxes on countries and giving the
 money raised to the GPGI.
 However, as we indicated in the discussion following 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "(Almost-a-neutrality"

\end_inset

, as far as the effect on voluntary contributions is concerned, this is
 approximately equivalent to considering the money as coming from 'outside',
 i.e.
 as being raised from non-contributors, given how small contributions for
 GPGIs are relative to GDP for any given country (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Implications-for-the opportunity costs"

\end_inset

).
 Thus proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "PMF crowding in and out"

\end_inset

 seems applicable.
 In particular, the disucssion following 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "PMF crowding in and out"

\end_inset

 applies.
 One general conclusion that we obtained from the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ_{a}}{dF}|_{F=0}=\frac{\text{\ensuremath{\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(0)}\frac{q_{i,a}}{Q}\left(\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}+\frac{Q-Q_{a}}{Q}(\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}})\right)\frac{1}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}}}}{\text{1}\text{+\text{\ensuremath{\sum_{i\in Contributors_{a}(0)}\frac{q_{i,a}}{Q_{a}}\frac{-\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}}{\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}}}}}}$
\end_inset

 is that the more concave the benefits of the GPGI as a function of its
 available funding, (i.e.
 the smaller the
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}$
\end_inset

), the worse.
 Thus other things equal, it is better to include GPGIs that do not have
 strongly diminishing marginal benefits.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another consequence of this formula is that it is good if the GPGIs included
 in the PMG are such that the countries contributing voluntarily strongly
 prefer one of them over the other, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{1}}-\frac{\sum_{b\neq a}\frac{Q_{b}}{Q-Q_{a}}\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{b}}}{\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q_{a}}}$
\end_inset

 is large.
 This might be an important argument for including GPGIs with strongly dispersed
 payoffs such as a RES-Fund (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "RES-Fund IRENA"

\end_inset

) and/or a Global Fund to reward countries as a function of carbon emissions
 and carbon taxes (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exa:A-Proposed-Global carbon tax incentive"

\end_inset

) in addition to GPGIs dedicated to preventing global pandemics, such as
 CEPI, even if the latter score better under criterion 1).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thirdly, the distribution of payoffs might affect the probability that the
 PMF will be adopted for using the revenues from deep sea resources.
 It is likely important that all countries can be confident that channelling
 the global revenues to the PMF will end up leading to an equilibirum giving
 them a higher payoff than under the counterfactual (which appears to entail
 the paying out the money generated from global resources to all countries).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The GPGI selection problem for the MCT mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is a set of governments who are interested in the MCT proposal.
 Consider the decision problem of the set of people who have the opportunity
 to give advice to these governments.
 Which GPGIs should they recommend as eligible for the MCT? There are least
 three important considerations to be taken into account:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) The global benefit, evaluated from an impartial perspective, that is
 generated per additional dollar available for the GPGI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) The crowding out/ crowding in of voluntary contributions to the GPGIs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) The incentives for governments to participate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4) The incentives for governments to choose the status with the right to
 influence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concerning 1), the discussion provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-GPGI-selection PMF"

\end_inset

 applies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to assess 2), the question arises as to how one should model the
 introduction of the MCT.
 One approach to modelling this would be as a subgame perfect Nash equilibrium
 of a two stage game, where in the first stage countries play the game induced
 by the MCT mechanism and in the second stage countries play the voluntary
 contribution game.
 In this case, we should dampen our optimism about the potential of the
 MCT, to the extent that there is crowding out.
 This is because in the first stage of the game countries will anticipate
 the crowding out and thus the benefit that they ascribe to money being
 directed via the MCT mechanism to a GPGI.
 To put it more precisely: Suppose the benefit for country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 per money directed to GPGI 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the relevant payoff in the first stage of the game is actually 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\frac{dQ_{k}}{dF})\theta_{i}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, in this model crowding out would not only lessen the impact of the
 money raised via the MCT mechanism for the GPGIs, it would also make it
 less likely that the MCT mechanism would have full (or even any) participation.
 From the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dQ}{dF}=\frac{\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}{1-\sum_{i\in Contributors}\frac{\epsilon_{u_{i}'}}{\epsilon_{h_{i}'}}\frac{q_{i}}{Q+F}}$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Crowding-out for exogenous donation to a given GPGI"

\end_inset

) we see that this again provides a rationale for selecting GPGIs whose
 benefits are not too concave, i.e.
 for which the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}$
\end_inset

 are not too small.
 Under the alternative modelling approach, where the players simultaneously
 choose their status and allocation in the MCT and their voluntary contributions
 there would similarly be crowding out, but this would not directly diminish
 the participation incentives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let us turn to 3) and 4).
 3) is clearly, since participation incentives have to be sufficient, ideally
 to end up inducing full participation.
 4) is important since the more players choose the status with the right
 to influence, the more money will be raised for GPGIs, which is valuable
 not only because of its direct benefit but also because this confers more
 legitimacy to the mechanism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As far as the participation incentives are concerned, it is good for the
 set of eligible GPGIs to be such that the players stronlgy prefer some
 GPGI over the others.
 In fact, this will be good for both 3) and 4), since it will increase the
 players' gains from participating with the right to influence.
 Again, this might be an important argument for including GPGIs with strongly
 dispersed payoffs such as a RES-Fund (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "RES-Fund IRENA"

\end_inset

) and/or a Global Fund to reward countries as a function of carbon emissions
 and carbon taxes (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "exa:A-Proposed-Global carbon tax incentive"

\end_inset

) in addition to GPGIs dedicated to preventing global pandemics, such as
 CEPI, even if the latter score better under criterion 1).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "7 sec:Combining-the-MCT"

\end_inset

 we will explore extensions to the MCT mechanism that could improve the
 situation in regard to 2), 3) and 4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "6 sec:How-to-learn"

\end_inset

How to learn from past data about crowding in and crowding out?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One approach would be to study the few cases where countries have introduced
 taxes to finance global institutions, for example the case of France in
 2006.
 However, the situation for the countries who introduced the solidarity
 levy on air tickets might have been quite different: Since few countries
 participated in the mechanism, introducing the tax and transferring the
 money to UNITAID was very similar to making a voluntary contribution from
 the general budget.
 The governments could thus get diplomatic credit for an act of altruism
 in a similar way to making a voluntary contribution.
 Moreover, domestic actors could accuse the government of giving away money
 without pursuing national interest in just the same way as is the case
 for voluntary contributions.
 As we have already pointed out, this would not be the case for a Nash equilibri
um with full participation under the MCT mechanism.
 In this case the government would still need to make voluntary contributions
 to GPGIs in order to get diplomatic recognition for its altruism.
 Moverover, domestic actors could only accuse it for being too generous
 on the basis of the amount of the voluntary contribution.
 The same arguments apply to the case of contributions to GPGIs coming from
 international seabed resources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If this line of reasoning is correct, then we cannot rely on the past example
 of taxes financing GPGIs to learn about crowding in and crowding out.
 Instead, a more promising approach might be to try to estimate the elasticities
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i}'}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{h_{i}'}^{a}$
\end_inset

 and then plug the estimates into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Crowding-out for exogenous donation to a given GPGI"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "PMF crowding in and out"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Empirical estimation of the elasticities 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{u_{i,a}'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{h_{i,a}'}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yet to be done.
\end_layout

